%S A397697 0,0,1,0,0,1,2,1,0,0,0,2,0,3,2,1,0,0,1,0,1,4,3,2,1,0,0,1,0,3,0,3,1,7,
%T A397697 6,5,4,3,2,1,0,0,1,1,1,3,1,6,5,4,3,2,1,0,0,0,2,0,0,2,6,4,2,0,9,8,7,6,
%U A397697 5,4,3,2,1,0,0,1,0,1,1,3,0,5,3,1,10,9,8,7
%N A397697 Triangle read by rows, where the n-th row contains the values of A018804(n) mod m, for m = 1 to A018804(n).
%C A397697 Stopping at m = A018804(n) captures the complete dynamic remainder lifecycle of the function before it stabilizes into a trivial linear countdown.
%C A397697 The maximum value in the row n is floor((A018804(n) - 1) / 2), achieved at the divisor position m = floor(A018804(n) / 2) + 1.
%C A397697 The number of zeros in the n-th row is given by A000005(A018804(n)).
%C A397697 The row sum of the n-th row is given by Sum_{m=1..A018804(n)} T(n,m) = A018804(n)^2 - Sum_{m=1..A018804(n)} A000203(m).
%C A397697 When the rows are normalized onto the unit square [0,1] x [0,1] via (m/A018804(n), (A018804(n) mod m)/A018804(n)), the points asymptotically cluster along distinct string-like structures (see Links section, "curtains" in a397697.png).
%H A397697 Ctibor O. Zizka, <a href="/A397697/a397697.png">Superimposed and normalized</a>
%H A397697 Ctibor O. Zizka, <a href="/A397697/a397697_1.png">First 10000 terms</a>
%F A397697 T(n, m) = A018804(n) mod m for 1 <= m <= A018804(n).
%e A397697 The triangular array begins:
%e A397697   n=1: 0
%e A397697   n=2: 0, 1, 0
%e A397697   n=3: 0, 1, 2, 1, 0
%e A397697   ...
%e A397697 For example, row n = 3 evaluates A018804(3) = 5. The remainders of 5 modulo m for m = 1 to 5 are 0, 1, 2, 1, 0.
%Y A397697 Cf. A000005, A000203, A018804.
%K A397697 tabf,look,nonn,new
%O A397697 1,7
%A A397697 _Ctibor O. Zizka_, Jul 05 2026
